In TypeScript, you can use type guards to convey to the type system that you know a value will only have a specific type, even though it might theoretically have multiple types. Type guards are functions or patterns that can narrow down the type of a variable.

Here are a few common ways to create type guards:

### 1. Using `typeof` for primitive types
If you have a value that is a primitive type, you can use `typeof` to create a type guard.

```typescript
function isString(value: any): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string';
}

let maybeString: string | number;
if (isString(maybeString)) {
  // At this point, TypeScript knows `maybeString` is definitely a string.
  console.log(maybeString.toUpperCase());
} else {
  console.log("Not a string");
}
```

### 2. Using `instanceof` for objects
If you have a value that is an instance of a class, you can use `instanceof` to create a type guard.

```typescript
class Animal {}
class Dog extends Animal {}

function isDog(value: any): value is Dog {
  return value instanceof Dog;
}

let maybeDog: Animal | Dog;
if (isDog(maybeDog)) {
  // At this point, TypeScript knows `maybeDog` is definitely a Dog.
  console.log(maybeDog.bark());
} else {
  console.log("Not a dog");
}
```

### 3. Using custom type checks
You can also create custom type checks using type predicates.

```typescript
type MaybeString = string | number;

function isString(value: MaybeString): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string';
}

let maybeString: MaybeString;
if (isString(maybeString)) {
  // At this point, TypeScript knows `maybeString` is definitely a string.
  console.log(maybeString.toUpperCase());
} else {
  console.log("Not a string");
}
```

### 4. Using `in` for object properties
If you have a value that might be an object with certain properties, you can use the `in` operator to create a type guard.

```typescript
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

let maybePerson: Person | number;

if ('name' in maybePerson) {
  // At this point, TypeScript knows `maybePerson` is definitely a Person.
  console.log(maybePerson.name);
} else {
  console.log("Not a Person");
}
```

By using these type guards, you can tell the TypeScript type system that you have additional information about the type of a value, allowing it to perform more accurate type checks and provide better type inference.

